# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 20:14:52
overview:<p>The Deva is the heavier of the two heavy-class Celestial OmniMechs, a seventy-ton design that serves as the series' primary close-combat platform. Named for celestial beings from Hindu and Buddhist tradition, the Deva entered production in 3069 at Gibson Federated BattleMechs and Martinson Armaments facilities. Strikingly similar in profile to its sixty-ton sibling the Grigori, the Deva fills a distinctly different battlefield role, closing with the enemy to deliver concentrated direct fire while its lighter partner provides missile support at range. For Coalition MechWarriors, the Deva became the Celestial they were most likely to face in close combat, and the one they learned to fear accordingly.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Deva is constructed on a Celestial Series DV1E endo steel chassis and powered by an Inspiration 280 light fusion engine, providing a top speed of sixty-four kilometers per hour. A heavy-duty gyro absorbs punishment that would cripple a standard unit, while the small cockpit common to all Celestials accommodates Manei Domini cybernetic interfaces. Thirteen and a half tons of Durallex Divine Protector standard armor give the design robust survivability. Twenty-nine and a half tons of pod space allow for substantial weapon configurations, and a fixed C3i computer enables coordinated fire within Manei Domini formations.</p><p>The Invictus configuration emphasizes direct fire support with a Gauss rifle and three light PPCs, supplemented by a retractable blade for melee engagements. The single ton of Gauss ammunition reflects an assumption that engagements will be short and decisive. Other configurations range from long-range sniper platforms with dual ER PPCs to close-assault loadouts featuring Ultra autocannons and jump jets, demonstrating the chassis's adaptability.</p>

deployment:<p>The custom configuration designated Achilleus serves as a personalized loadout tailored to its Manei Domini pilot's enhanced cybernetic capabilities and combat doctrine. The weapon selection exploits the Deva's generous pod capacity and heavy-duty gyro to mount an aggressive combination of armaments that maximizes the operator's augmented reflexes and tactical awareness. The heavy-duty gyro allows the pilot to sustain damage that would cripple other designs, enabling the aggressive close-range tactics favored by the most experienced Domini operatives.</p>

history:<p>The Deva earned the Celestial series its fearsome combat reputation through a string of engagements that left Coalition commands deeply shaken. Where the Malak surprised and the Seraph intimidated, the Deva fought, and its combat record became the benchmark against which Coalition planners measured the Celestial threat. After-action reports from surviving units consistently highlighted the Deva's combination of accurate fire, punishing resilience, and the fanatical aggression of its Manei Domini pilots as a qualitatively different challenge from anything they had previously encountered.</p><p>Among the recorded Celestial engagements, a Deva piloted by Demi-Precentor Eric Hughes fought against Clan Nova Cat forces and conventional armor on Luthien in August 3072. The Crane district engagement in Nagasaki demonstrated both the design's combat prowess and the fanatical determination of its pilots, who fought without regard for personal survival in defense of Word of Blake positions on the occupied world. Hughes's Deva sustained catastrophic armor damage across multiple engagements but continued fighting, its heavy-duty gyro absorbing hits that would have toppled lesser machines. The Luthien campaign became a case study in Celestial combat effectiveness, as a relatively small number of Manei Domini 'Mechs inflicted disproportionate casualties on forces that significantly outnumbered them.</p><p>The Seventh Division's Bells of Faith III-lambda fielded Devas prominently throughout the Jihad, with Precentor VII Seth Smith-Solomon piloting one of the design's more notable examples. Smith-Solomon's deployment patterns reflected the Deva's versatility, shifting between sniper and brawler configurations depending on mission requirements. Coalition intelligence eventually compiled engagement profiles for known Deva pilots, noting that the design's operators displayed an unusually high degree of tactical sophistication even by Manei Domini standards. The Opacus Venatori also maintained Devas in their inventory, with Adept Achilleus St. John operating a custom configuration built around experimental large variable speed pulse lasers linked to a targeting computer for extreme precision at close range.</p><p>Coalition after-action analyses eventually identified the Deva's heavy-duty gyro as a critical factor in its combat performance. Standard engagement doctrine called for targeting an opponent's legs and gyro to force a fall, but the Deva's reinforced gyro shrugged off impacts that would have knocked down most seventy-ton designs. Revised tactical guidelines recommended concentrating fire on the center torso or attempting to destroy weapons rather than relying on knockdown tactics. These adaptations reduced Deva effectiveness somewhat in later engagements, but the design remained a dangerous opponent throughout the conflict.</p><p>Surviving Devas are among the more commonly encountered Celestials in the post-Jihad era, partly because their heavy-duty gyros and standard armor make them more maintainable than designs relying on more exotic structural components. The Exanimus variant, designed for underwater combat with UMU systems and torpedo launchers, further expanded the operational envelope. Remnant cells have occasionally fielded Devas in engagements through the Dark Age period, and the design's reputation as a lethal close-range combatant ensures that any confirmed sighting draws immediate attention from military intelligence. The Caelestis configuration, incorporating captured Clan binary laser cannons and a targeting computer, represented some of the most advanced technology mounted on any Inner Sphere design during the Jihad.</p>

